    localDetails: 'The university-named streets in the original Regents Park section see heavy mole activity because the oldest landscaping produces the richest soil. Properties along Emerson Street and Alameda Avenue, with their deep setbacks and mature trees, have especially active mole populations. The Fircrest Golf Club creates a concentration of irrigated turf that serves as a mole reservoir for surrounding blocks. Homes near Fircrest Park and the pool area deal with moles moving between the maintained park grounds and residential yards. The boundaries with Tacoma to the north and University Place to the south show no break in mole activity — the moles move freely across city lines through connected underground tunnel networks.',
