    whyMolesThrive: 'The Green River Valley was built by thousands of years of river flooding, depositing deep, rich alluvial soil across the valley floor. Before the Howard A. Hanson Dam was completed in 1962, annual floods continuously rebuilt the soil profile and kept it saturated. Today that same soil is deep, loamy, and still holds moisture thanks to the valley\'s high water table and 38+ inches of annual rainfall. Earthworm populations in valley soil are among the densest in King County, and Townsend\'s moles respond accordingly. The mix of residential yards, small farms, and the remaining agricultural land in the Lower Green River APD gives moles a permanent habitat reservoir.',
